Absolutely. It makes your code more robust and idiomatic in Rust. Here's a better way to handle this error:
```rust
use std::fs::File;
fn main() {
  match File::open("data.txt") {
    Ok(file) => {
        let mut reader = BufReader::new(file);
        // continue with your reading logic here
    }
    Err(e) => eprintln!("Error occurred: {}", e),
  }
}
```

No need to be so explicit in this case—Rust’s `File::open` naturally handles missing files by returning an appropriate `io::Error`. However, if you want more control (e.g., differentiate file not found from permission errors), then yes, use `match` or `.and_then()` further down the line. For now, your updated code is correct:
```rust
match File::open("data.txt") {
  Ok(file) => { /* continue */ }
  Err(e) => eprintln!("Error occurred: {}", e),
}
```
Good call on improving error handling!
